Colormaps are heavily utilized in the digital space, as they are often the bridge between 
colorless objects and their shading. A colormap uses points to navigate and project 
colors onto certain areas. For exampple, in my 3D modeling course, 2d images filled with 
colors called UV textures are used, and are projected onto a 2d image that stores all the 
geometric data for the shapes being colored. A cube for example, would have a UV map of 6 
squares, usually attached for ease of use, and the texture would be a colored overlay 
that projects those colors onto those squares when plugged in in the 3d software. 

According to https://matplotlib.org/stable/users/explain/colors/colormaps.html, colormaps in python are similar in that they contain gradients that help the processor to interpret and attach colors based on certain numerical values, so its a much more technical method than a visual image being plugged in like a map.